rest_of_day_open: I am likely going to be relaxing as I have finished my midterms, play tennis with my friends within the next few days and go out to eat dinner a few times. I'll spend a lot of time reselling in my area to make some money to save while I can before I get on campus.
critical_positive: The other person in the conversation was able to ask many questions to keep it flowing between topics by either asking about something brought up earlier, or ask a new question that was somewhat related. We brought up life experiences from beyond the conversation to supplement and add new information.
critical_negative: There were a few moments where it was difficult to tell when the conversation partner was done speaking about the conversation, and resulted in times when I would start speaking before my conversation partner was done speaking. This meant that I would forget what he said while I spoke accidentaly.

rest_of_day_open: Well, looks like things are about to get unpleasant again. My dad had a heart attack and is coming home from rehab on Friday; my mom is terrified because he's a large man but physically weak, and she can't help him get up if he falls, which he tends to do. Earlier this year I spent about a month living at their house to watch over him, and I don't mind it except my mom is one of those covid deniers and she blithely goes out for haircuts and pedicures and restaurants and other places and it's not fair to me. But maybe she'll get a nurse or something. Now that I've written all this I'm depressed!
critical_positive: He was friendly and open and responsive to whatever I asked about. We're both musicians, so we had that to talk about. We could also talk about gaming, which I do a lot, and California, where I lived for about 20 years, and I'm very familiar with Berkeley, where he'll be going to college.
critical_negative: He's young, not especially socially experienced, and it felt like if I didn't ask a question or bring up a topic, we would have sat there staring at each other. I didn't mind leading the conversation, but there are only so many things to talk about with a college age kid.
